For newer versions of photoshop, you can also do one of several other things.<br>
First, (provided your currenly selected layer is an editable layer, not a text layer or something) you can make your marquee selection box and go to Edit-&gt;Stroke. Select your line width, color, opacity, etc and voila!<br>
However, that still uses the selection tool, which isn't really a drawing tool. You can use the shape tools (next to the pen tool) to draw rectangles (or other stuff). Edit them however you want with points. Among other ways, you can switch over to your Paths tab (same place as the layers and channels). Select the path you want to use (if you're not making new ones, this'll just be the &quot;Work Path&quot; one). Click on that little arrow in the top right and select Stroke Path (reminder, you also have to have an editable layer selected to do this). With this you can stroke the path with most of the other tools in their current settings. You can also simulate pressure and all that (which would be more useful for say, digitally inking with the pen tool). Paths are a little odd to get used to (especially if you haven't used fully vector based programs like Illustrator or Freehand), but they're probably the most robust, flexible way to do boxes and other stuff like that in.<br>
If you want a selection too, you can easily convert a path to a selection too. <br>
<br>
